ober 2016</span></span> </b>in Kalangala district in collaboration with METS.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','UgandaEMR training Kalangala','','publish','closed','closed','','ugandaemr-training-kalangala','','','2016-10-14 08:40:54','2016-10-14 08:40:54','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8280',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8281,1,'2016-10-11 06:05:24','2016-10-11 06:05:24','&nbsp;\r\n<div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div>Viral load monitoring has been recommended by WHO/UNAIDS as the gold standard test to determine the HIV patients response to the Anti-retroviral therapy. In addition to optimizing treatment outcomes, viral load is a particularly useful tool for monitoring adherence to treatment, treatment failure and performing sentinel surveillance.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','2nd National Viral Load Monitoring training','','publish','closed','closed','','2nd-national-viral-load-monitoring-training','','','2016-10-14 08:39:21','2016-10-14 08:39:21','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8281',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8289,2,'2016-10-11 08:58:26','2016-10-11 08:58:26','','img_5927','','inherit','open','closed','','img_5927','','','2016-10-11 08:58:26','2016-10-11 08:58:26','',7780,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/IMG_5927.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8291,2,'2016-10-11 09:07:24','2016-10-11 09:07:24','','20160719_110550','Rose Baryamutuma making a presentation at the DREAMS training for Mildmay and Rakai at RHSP','inherit','open','closed','','20160719_110550','','','2016-10-11 09:12:33','2016-10-11 09:12:33','',7759,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/20160719_110550.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8309,2,'2016-10-14 08:11:57','2016-10-14 08:11:57','http://vldash.cphluganda.org/\r\n\r\nMETS is giving Technical Support to the MoH - CPHL to develop a dashboard to monitor Viral Load. This meeting will host stakeholders to discuss matters that will strengthen and compliment the system','Viral Load Stakeholders\' meeting','','publish','closed','closed','','viral-load-stakeholders-meeting','','','2016-10-14 08:37:43','2016-10-14 08:37:43','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8309',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8310,2,'2016-10-14 08:29:15','2016-10-14 08:29:15','The Local Governments/Districts are the units of implementation but are structurally linked to the central government through line ministries with well-defined mandates. Some of the key functions for the local governments include but are not limited to; Planning, coordination and monitoring the delivery of services in accordance with national policies. For the health sector in particular, the District Health Office is mandated to spearhead these functions under the stewardship of the Ministry of Health (MoH). Often times, however, local governments lack the capacity to effectively fulfil their stipulated mandates. Against this background, the Makerere University School of Public Health-CDC HIV/AIDS Fellowship Program (MakSPH-CDC) in collaboration with the Ministry of Health and supported by Centers for Disease Control (CDC), designed a Medium term fellowship for mangers of health services in the district with the sole aim of strengthening their capacity in Leadership, Governance and Management (GLM).','Fellowship in Governance Leadership and Management','','publish','closed','closed','','fellowship-in-governance-leadership-and-management','','','2016-10-14 08:36:57','2016-10-14 08:36:57','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8310',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8311,2,'2016-10-14 08:34:09','2016-10-14 08:34:09','METS Monitoring and Evaluation Team will visit fifteen Districts to carry out mentor-ship for the M&amp;E Fellowship Program','Mentorship Visits','','publish','closed','closed','','mentorship-visits','','','2016-10-14 08:34:09','2016-10-14 08:34:09','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8311',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8312,2,'2016-10-14 09:09:11','2016-10-14 09:09:11','Development of District profiles for CDC supported Districts','Development of District profiles','','publish','closed','closed','','development-of-district-profiles','','','2016-10-14 09:09:11','2016-10-14 09:09:11','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8312',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8313,2,'2016-10-14 09:15:56','2016-10-14 09:15:56','Workshops for Development of Bulletins for CDC Districts will be held in Mityana/Gulu/Mbale and Masaka','Development of Bulletins','','publish','closed','closed','','development-of-bulletins','','','2016-10-14 09:15:56','2016-10-14 09:15:56','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8313',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8324,2,'2016-10-20 15:33:03','2016-10-20 15:33:03','METS PARTNERS WITH SSESE ISLANDS\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8357\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-8357\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/IMG_6559-1-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"Participants in the Ssese DHIS2 training. Seated L-R: KCPHS Project Manager Christine Zawedde, METS Program Manager Evelyn Akello, CDC Data Management Specialist Patrick Omiel and HMIS Coordinator Stephen Ocaya\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> Participants in the Ssese DHIS2 training. Seated L-R: KCPHS Project Manager Christine Zawedde, METS Program Manager Evelyn Akello, CDC Data Management Specialist Patrick Omiel and HMIS Coordinator Stephen Ocaya[/caption]\r\n\r\nMets Program engaged the Ssese Islands Health Facility staff in a five day DHIS2 training. The training targeted 20 people but over 30 health personnel participated. These included nurses, Medical Records Assistants, Volunteers at KHCIV, clinical Officers and M&amp;E Officers. The District Health Office was well represented by the District Bio-Statistican and the HMIS Focal Person.\r\nThe Ministry of Health (MoH) has been implementing various tools to collect its data from health facilities. District Health Information Software-Version 2 (DHIS2) is one of these tools used to collect, validate, analyse, and used in presentation of aggregate statistical data, tailored to integrated health information management activities. It is a generic tool that allows for the customization of the contents of a specific information system without the need to program. The training included data quality and presentation, data entry, DHIS2 messaging, data validation, GIS map, innovations, pivot tables and the dashboard (data visualizer).\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8328\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-8328\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/IMG_6493-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"Nathan Kayemba from Mazinga HC III takes participants through the challenges data entrants face that result into poor data\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> Nathan Kayemba from Mazinga HC III takes participants through the challenges data entrants face that result into poor data[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe participants were from fourteen health facilities across the Ssese Islands and the Kalangala Comprehensive Public Health Services (KCPHS)Project. The facilities included Kalangala HC IV (KHCIV), Bufumira HC III, Mugoye HC III, Ssese Island African AIDS Project (SIAAP)-Bugoma HCII, Lujjabwa Island HCII, Bukasa HC IV, Lulamba HC III, Bwendero HC III, Mazinga HC III, Mulabana HC II, St. Elizabeth Bumangi HC II, Bubeke HC III, Kasekulo HC II and Kachanga HC II.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8327\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"200\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-8327\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/IMG_6538-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"Ms. Evelyn Akello, Program Manager METS\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" /> Ms. Evelyn Akello, Program Manager METS[/caption]\r\n\r\nMs. Evelyn Akello, Program Manager METS emphasized the need for continued use of the system as this was the one sure way to master it, she however cautioned that the paper based system should not be entirely dropped by users in the different health facilities.\r\n\r\nThe training was conducted by HMIS Coordinator Stephen Ocaya, HIS Analysts Jonathan Mpango and  Milton Kaye; all from METS and CDC facilitator Patrick Omiel\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','SSESE ISLANDS HEALTH OFFICIALS TRAINNING','','publish','open','open','','mets-partners-in-ssese-islands','','','2016-11-05 07:04:02','2016-11-05 07:04:02','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?p=8324',0,'post','',0),(8325,2,'2016-10-20 15:20:22','2016-10-20 15:20:22','','img_6559','','inherit','open','closed','','img_6559','','','2016-10-20 15:20:22','2016-10-20 15:20:22','',8324,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/IMG_6559.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8326,2,'2016-10-20 15:20:58','2016-10-20 15:20:58','','img_6533','','inherit','open','closed','','img_6533','','','2016-10-20 15:20:58','2016-10-20 15:20:58','',8324,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/IMG_6533.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8327,2,'2016-10-20 15:22:28','2016-10-20 15:22:28','','img_6538','Ms. Evelyn Akello, Program Manager METS','inherit','open','closed','','img_6538','','','2016-11-01 08:58:48','2016-11-01 08:58:48','',8324,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/IMG_6538.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8328,2,'2016-10-20 15:25:23','2016-10-20 15:25:23','','img_6493','Nathan Kayemba from Mazinga HC III takes participants through the challenges data entrants face that result into poor data','inherit','open','closed','','img_6493','','','2016-11-01 09:01:24','2016-11-01 09:01:24','',8324,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/IMG_6493.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8329,2,'2016-10-20 15:32:44','2016-10-20 15:32:44','','dhis2-training-kalangala','','inherit','open','closed','','dhis2-training-kalangala','','','2016-10-20 15:32:44','2016-10-20 15:32:44','',8324,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/DHIS2-training-Kalangala.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(8334,2,'2016-10-28 14:00:39','2016-10-28 14:00:39','','img_6416','','inherit','open','closed','','img_6416','','','2016-10-28 14:00:39','2016-10-28 14:00:39','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/IMG_6416.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8337,1,'2016-10-31 10:32:26','2016-10-31 10:32:26','','openmrs-logo','','inherit','open','closed','','openmrs-logo','','','2016-10-31 10:32:26','2016-10-31 10:32:26','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/openmrs-logo.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(8342,2,'2016-11-01 08:26:00','2016-11-01 08:26:00','<a href=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/CBS-Launch-Kabarole.doc\">cbs-launch-kabarole</a>','METS launches HIV Case Based Surveillance in Kabarole','','publish','closed','closed','','mets-launches-hiv-case-based-surveillance-in-kabarole','','','2016-11-01 08:26:00','2016-11-01 08:26:00','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?page_id=8342',0,'page','',0),(8343,2,'2016-11-01 08:21:18','2016-11-01 08:21:18','','cbs-launch-kabarole','','inherit','open','closed','','cbs-launch-kabarole','','','2016-11-01 08:21:18','2016-11-01 08:21:18','',8342,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/CBS-Launch-Kabarole.doc',0,'attachment','application/msword',0),(8344,2,'2016-11-01 08:23:17','2016-11-01 08:23:17','','img_5446','','inherit','open','closed','','img_5446','','','2016-11-01 08:23:17','2016-11-01 08:23:17','',8342,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_5446.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8347,2,'2016-11-01 08:34:03','2016-11-01 08:34:03','Makerere School of Public Health Monitoring and Evaluation Technical Support (MakSPH-METS) Program Launches Case Based Surveillance (CBS) in Uganda\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_7807\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-7807\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/kabalole_1-300x107.jpg\" alt=\"A cross section of the equipment that was donated by MakSPH-METS Program to Kabarole District \" width=\"300\" height=\"107\" /> A cross section of the equipment that was donated by MakSPH-METS Program to Kabarole District[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe skies cleared to pave way for the much anticipated inauguration of the HIV Case Based Surveillance Project that took place in Kabarole District on 2nd August 2016 at Kicwamba Health Centre (HC) III. The HC, located at the foot of magnificent hills, has for a long time depended on paper to document the information of its patients undergoing ART like many others throughout the country. However, with the launch of the CBS project, this is expected to change to a computerized system that will enable health workers acquire accurate and unduplicated information regarding the number of people that are infected by HIV within the District and track their movement and progress under treatment.\r\nCBS is one of the program areas of METS and it has been piloted in two Districts in Uganda; Hoima and Kabarole. The choice of Districts was coined basing on various factors among them the state of the facilities and the prevalence rates in each District. Uganda is among the first countries to adapt CBS as has been done in Ethiopia, Kenya, South Africa and Tanzania.\r\nMakSPH in partnership with the Ministry of Health donated equipment worth approximately Ugx 97.6 million to Kabarole District. This included 19 computer and 10 solar system panels. The solar panels will be installed in the Health Centers that are off the UMEME grid and therefore cannot access electricity. The beneficiary centers include Kabarole Hospital, Fort Portal Referral, Kasenda, Kicwamba, Kakinga, Kiddubuli, Iruhuura, Nyataboma, Nyabuuswa, Rwagiimba, Rwambiya, Kiiko, Kabende, Kasenda, Kisomoro, Kiyoombya, Kiibaate, Kabonyeenero.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8351\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-8351\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_5424-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"Professor Anthony Mbonye and METS staff hands over the equipment to the District leadership\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> Professor Anthony Mbonye and METS staff hands over the equipment to the District leadership[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8352\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-8352\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_5366-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"A section of the residents of surrounding areas of Kicwamba HC III \" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> A section of the residents of surrounding areas of Kicwamba HC III[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe event was graced by Professor Anthony Mbonye, who represented the Minister of Health, the Commissioner Disease Control Dr. Patrick Tusiime, Dr. Alex Opio, Richard Rwabuhinga the Kabarole LCV Chairman, the District CAO Mr. Dastan Balaba, the DHO Dr. Nathan Ruhinda, a Ministry of Health Delegation, various officers from Implementing Partner organizations like Baylor Uganda and several District leaders. The well attended inauguration was kick started with a band that marched and thrilled the crowds to the venue.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8353\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-8353\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_5415-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"Professor Mbonye making his remarks during the inauguration; others L–R: Dr. Tusiime, Dr. Opio, Dr. Musinguzi and Mr. Balaba\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> Professor Mbonye making his remarks during the inauguration; others L–R: Dr. Tusiime, Dr. Opio, Dr. Musinguzi and Mr. Balaba[/caption]\r\n\r\nProfessor Mbonye noted that the efforts by CDC, MakSPH-METS and other Implementing Partners who are assisting Government in realizing its goals while enabling proper knowledge about the HIV/AIDS burden in the various sections of the country. He added that the Ministry of Health would soon launch an HIV Impact Survey that would give new estimates in this regard.\r\nHon. Richard Rwabuhinga applauded METS for succeeding in becoming a household name as this in itself was an achievement because people out there know that something good is being done. He further applauded the METS team for mentoring the necessary staff in the district especially in regard to data management. He pledged to put in place required security for the systems to ensure continued utilization.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8354\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-8354\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_5393-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"The DHO (in suit) Dr. Nathan Ruhinda, introduces the Kicwamba HC III staff\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> The DHO (in suit) Dr. Nathan Ruhinda, introduces the Kicwamba HC III staff[/caption]\r\n\r\nDr. Ruhinda expressed his commitment to ensure the Electronic Medical Records System is given all the necessary support seeing as the District was well organized and has the will to work with the partners on ground. He also appreciated the innovation that was linking the facilities as this would ease monitoring of patients.\r\nMETS Program Manager Ms. Evelyn Akello, who spoke on behalf of the Principal Investigator Professor William Bazeyo, noted that the CBS would empower the fight against HIV/AIDS as it would be an addition to other important sero-behavioral surveys, size estimation studies of risk groups and sentinel surveillance to form a more complete picture of the HIV epidemic going forward. Data from these would assist in planning and prioritization of HIV prevention and intervention activities. She further pledged technical support to clinics being linked through a networked biometric patient management system that uses finger print technology and the national identification cards.\r\nThe next phases will include finger print taking of the patients as well as continued training on use of the program. The success of this project will pave way for efforts of spreading these best practices to the rest of the districts.','Launch of the HIV Case Based Surveillance Project - Kabarole','','publish','open','open','','launch-of-the-hiv-case-based-surveillance-project-kabarole','','','2016-11-01 09:10:07','2016-11-01 09:10:07','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?p=8347',0,'post','',0),(8351,2,'2016-11-01 08:43:31','2016-11-01 08:43:31','','img_5424','Professor Anthony Mbonye and METS staff hands over the equipment to the District leadership','inherit','open','closed','','img_5424','','','2016-11-01 08:43:43','2016-11-01 08:43:43','',8347,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_5424.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8352,2,'2016-11-01 08:44:47','2016-11-01 08:44:47','','img_5366','A section of the residents of surrounding areas of Kicwamba HC III ','inherit','open','closed','','img_5366','','','2016-11-01 08:45:07','2016-11-01 08:45:07','',8347,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_5366.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8353,2,'2016-11-01 08:46:50','2016-11-01 08:46:50','','img_5415','Professor Mbonye making his remarks during the inauguration; others L–R: Dr. Tusiime, Dr. Opio, Dr. Musinguzi and Mr. Balaba','inherit','open','closed','','img_5415','','','2016-11-01 08:47:04','2016-11-01 08:47:04','',8347,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_5415.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8354,2,'2016-11-01 08:49:47','2016-11-01 08:49:47','','img_5393','The DHO (in suit) Dr. Nathan Ruhinda, introduces the Kicwamba HC III staff','inherit','open','closed','','img_5393','','','2016-11-01 08:50:10','2016-11-01 08:50:10','',8347,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_5393.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8359,2,'2016-11-01 09:23:28','2016-11-01 09:23:28','<strong>HIV Case Based Surveillance implementation in Kabarole</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Introduction</strong>\r\nCase Based Surveillance (CBS) was recommended by the World Health Organisation (WHO) as early as 2006 and is currently being implemented in a few countries such as Kenya, Ethiopia, South Africa, Tanzania and Namibia. Uganda has now joined these countries by adopting CBS as a means of monitoring trends of HIV infections in the country. In Uganda, CBS is being implemented by the Makerere University School of Public Health - Monitoring and Evaluation Technical Support Program (METS) in partnership with the Ministry of Health, Kabarole and Hoima District Local Governments.\r\n\r\n<strong>CBS as a HIV disease monitoring tool of choice</strong>\r\nCBS allows for unique identification and characterization of persons newly diagnosed with HIV or AIDS and tracking them over time. It provides data on persons at risk to better inform and target programming. Data from individual cases provides more detailed information on the epidemiology of HIV including district-based estimates of prevalent infection, disease trends to include stage of disease at diagnosis, changes in CD4 count, time to viral suppression, proportion of cases virally suppressed, the incidence of opportunistic infections, and mortality, as well as time from diagnosis to entering care, adherence and retention.\r\n\r\n<strong>Mode of CBS implementation</strong>\r\nThe foundation of CBS is Electronic Medical records (EMR) which allows for fast searching, deduplication and analysis of patient data. The EMR in use is OpenMRS which was upgraded by METS from version 1.6.3 to 1.11.6. The newer version has the revised HMIS data collection and reporting tools of the Ministry of Health. OpenMRS enhances efficient patient management in addition to monitoring of performance indicators that relate to key CBS sentinel events.\r\n\r\nImplementation of CBS began with an infrastructure assessment that was done by METS together with Ministry of Health, Baylor Uganda, and the District Health teams to determine the availability of computer equipment, supporting human resource and power infrastructure that would be required to run OpenMRS at facility level.\r\n\r\nUsing findings from the assessment, METS procured computers and solar systems for facilities that did not have any source of power in Kabarole. These were installed with OpenMRS and facility staff were trained on data management including analysis.\r\n\r\n<strong>How CBS has changed the medical landscape</strong>\r\nFollowing installation/upgrade of OpenMRS, health facilities in Kabarole are now able to:\r\n• Autogenerate reports needed for Ministry of Health reporting. These reports include monthly, quarterly and annual reports. This has improved timeliness, correctness and completeness of reporting into DHIS2 by Kabarole District.\r\n• Minimise the loss to follow up of patients through tracking appointment keeping at facilities level. This is through auto-generation of the list of missed appointments to guide follow up through phone calls and home visits at community level hence fostering retention in care (2nd part of the 90-90-90 targets).\r\n• Track Viral Load Monitoring through auto-generation of clients who achieve and maintain Viral Load suppression (3rd part of the 90-90-90 targets)\r\n• Track progression of disease from the time of diagnosis through the continuum of care\r\n• Deduplication of clients who seek services at different health facilities within the same district.\r\n• Link mother and baby pairs to ensure retention in care.\r\n\r\nAs an intermediate outcome, CBS has improved budgeting and resource allocation for HIV and AIDS based on correct data since duplication of clients has been eliminated. With enhanced analysis, CBS has also improved use of data for decision making. It is currently a pilot by METS in the two districts of Kabarole and Hoima; hopefully it can be scaled up to other districts as a best practice.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','HIV Case Based Surveillance; Hope Restored','','publish','open','open','','8359-2','','','2016-11-01 09:41:05','2016-11-01 09:41:05','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?p=8359',0,'post','',0),(8360,2,'2016-11-01 09:14:38','2016-11-01 09:14:38','','img_0012','Equipment donated to Kabarole for CBS pilot being inspected  on arrival at the District Stores','inherit','open','closed','','img_0012','','','2016-11-01 09:15:50','2016-11-01 09:15:50','',8359,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/IMG_0012.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8365,2,'2016-11-01 09:51:58','2016-11-01 09:51:58','<strong>Integrating Tetanus Toxoid (TT) Vaccination into Voluntary Medical Male Circumcision</strong><strong> (VMMC) services</strong>\r\n\r\nThe 2011 Uganda AIDS indicator survey showed that less than 30% of men were circumcised. In response to the low male circumcision prevalence, the Uganda AIDS Commission (UAC) set a national target of 4.2 million male circumcisions to be performed by the end of 2015. The US Presidential Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR), through the Centres for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) supported this initiative. By October 2015, more than 2.6 million men (62.2% of the national target) had been circumcised.\r\n\r\nIn the period between 2013 and 2015, 9 cases of tetanus infection were reported in Uganda. Of these, 4 (44.4%) resulted into death. As a result, the World Health Organisation (WHO) recommended the integration of TT vaccination into VMMC services. Accordingly, the Ugandan Ministry of Health (MoH) adopted a two (2) dose TT vaccination program for VMMC clients. Tetanus Toxoid is a vaccine that is used to prevent against Tetanus which is a bacterial infection transmitted when the germs get into contact with broken skin, wound or cut.\r\n\r\nA Quality Improvement assessment carried out by the Makerere University School of Public Health (MakSPH) - Monitoring and Evaluation Technical Support (METS) Program showed that less than 20% of the VMMC sites were providing TT vaccination to their clients as recommended by the MoH. This was attributed to gaps identified in human resource knowledge and skills, inadequate guidelines, information and education materials on TT and lack of appropriate tools for TT data capture hence undermining the integration of TT vaccination into VMMC services.\r\n\r\nTo address the above challenges, METS, in collaboration with MoH supported trainings in Tetanus Toxoid (TT) vaccination for VMMC clients to 322 service providers in 57 CDC-supported VMMC sites. In addition, METS provided onsite mentorship and coaching in TT vaccination integration and supported the development of TT data capture tools which are currently in use at all the sites.\r\n\r\nAn evaluation conducted three months later showed that all the sites had effectively integrated the recommended TT vaccinations in their VMMC services and no new cases of tetanus infections have been reported since.','Our Journey to achieve Quality Improvement in VMMC','','publish','open','open','','our-journey-to-achieve-quality-improvement-in-vmmc','','','2016-11-01 09:51:58','2016-11-01 09:51:58','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?p=8365',0,'post','',0),(8369,2,'2016-11-02 09:13:54','2016-11-02 09:13:54','METS shall be conducting a pre-dissemination workshop for the 1st cohort of the M&amp;E fellows on 22-24 November to prepare them for the final dissemination workshop which is scheduled for November 25','Pre-dissemination workshop for the first M&E fellows cohort','','publish','closed','closed','','pre-dissemination-workshop-for-the-first-me-fellows-cohort','','','2016-11-23 11:19:54','2016-11-23 11:19:54','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8369',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8370,2,'2016-11-02 09:22:48','2016-11-02 09:22:48','METS will carry out site visits for Health Facilities in Kampala in preparation for the December OpenMRS Conference\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Site Mentor-ship for Health Facilities in Kampala','','publish','closed','closed','','site-mentor-ship-for-health-facilities-in-kampala','','','2016-11-02 09:22:48','2016-11-02 09:22:48','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8370',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8371,1,'2016-11-04 10:15:23','2016-11-04 10:15:23','','ucsf','','publish','closed','closed','','ucsf','','','2017-07-18 07:08:33','2017-07-18 07:08:33','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=partners&#038;p=8371',0,'partners','',0),(8372,1,'2016-11-04 10:21:33','2016-11-04 10:21:33','','Center for Disease Control','','pending','closed','closed','','center-for-disease-control','','','2017-05-18 12:25:46','2017-05-18 12:25:46','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=partners&#038;p=8372',0,'partners','',0),(8374,1,'2016-11-04 10:27:15','2016-11-04 10:27:15','','PEPFAR','','publish','closed','closed','','pepfar','','','2017-07-18 07:04:05','2017-07-18 07:04:05','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=partners&#038;p=8374',0,'partners','',0),(8376,1,'2016-11-04 10:29:34','2016-11-04 10:29:34','','MINISTRY OF HEALTH','','publish','closed','closed','','ministry-of-health-2','','','2017-07-18 06:10:56','2017-07-18 06:10:56','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=partners&#038;p=8376',0,'partners','',0),(8391,2,'2016-11-23 11:14:48','2016-11-23 11:14:48','In line with our mandate to reinforce the District and health facility capabilities in monitoring and evaluation, METS designed a short-term M&amp;E fellowship program for district bio statisticians and HMIS focal persons. The two modular fellowship program was aimed at building the capacity of the target persons in data management practices including collection, collation, analysis, presentation, dissemination and use of strategic information to inform decisions and planning at district and health facility levels. In addition, the fellows were supported to design M&amp;E projects for addressing critical M&amp;E gaps in their districts. The M&amp;E projects adopted the Plan-Do-Study-Act (PDSA) approach to quality improvement and mainly focused on improving HIV/AIDS data quality and use. A total of 30 fellows from 15 districts were enrolled into the fellowship program as the 1st cohort.\r\nThe meeting will provide an opportunity for the fellows to disseminate their project results to a wider HIV/AIDS stakeholder forum. This will involve sharing the project outcomes, best practices, lessons learnt and challenges in improving data quality for HIV/AIDS programs at district and health facility level. It is hoped that similar projects may be adopted and scaled nationally.','Final Dissemination Meeting for short-term M&E fellows','','publish','closed','closed','','final-dissemination-meeting-for-short-term-me-fellows','','','2016-11-23 11:14:48','2016-11-23 11:14:48','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8391',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8397,1,'2016-11-23 13:47:12','2016-11-23 13:47:12','','pref100x71','','inherit','open','closed','','pref100x71','','','2016-11-23 13:47:12','2016-11-23 13:47:12','',8372,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/pref100x71.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8398,2,'2016-11-29 10:04:20','2016-11-29 10:04:20','','Dr. Miriam Murungi','','publish','closed','closed','','dr-miriam-murungi','','','2017-04-04 13:46:59','2017-04-04 13:46:59','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=staff&#038;p=8398',0,'staff','',0),(8401,2,'2016-11-29 10:07:22','2016-11-29 10:07:22','','Sharon Abowe','','publish','closed','closed','','sharon-abowe','','','2016-11-29 10:07:22','2016-11-29 10:07:22','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=staff&#038;p=8401',0,'staff','',0),(8402,2,'2016-11-29 10:10:49','2016-11-29 10:10:49','','Ms. Evelyn Akello','','publish','closed','closed','','ms-evelyn-akello','','','2017-04-05 01:25:31','2017-04-05 01:25:31','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=staff&#038;p=8402',0,'staff','',0),(8407,2,'2016-11-29 10:23:46','2016-11-29 10:23:46','','Ms. Barbra Kusiima','','publish','closed','closed','','ms-barbra-kusiima','','','2017-04-04 13:49:50','2017-04-04 13:49:50','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=staff&#038;p=8407',0,'staff','',0),(8436,2,'2017-01-20 11:09:17','2017-01-20 11:09:17','6<sup>th</sup> December 2016 marked the opening of the historical OpenMRS International Implementers’ conference in Uganda themed <strong><em>“eHealth for better outcomes: Innovating and Strengthening Systems”</em></strong>. The first of its kind in the country, and the most attended yet in the history of its existence. The Uganda Ministry of Health with technical support from the Makerere University School of Public Health’s Monitoring and Evaluation Technical Support (METS) Program hosted the six-day conference at Speke Resort Munyonyo.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8440\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-8440 size-medium\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7270-300x177.jpg\" alt=\"IMG_7270\" width=\"300\" height=\"177\" /> L-R: Dr. Eddie Mukooyo (Assistant Commissioner DHI-MoH &amp; Chair Organizing Committee), Dr. Paul Biondich (OpenMRS Co-Founder and Project Lead) and Prof. Willaim Bazeyo (Dean MakSPH &amp; PI METS) during the opening of the Conference[/caption]\r\n\r\n350 delegates from 25 countries from around the world attended the 2016 Implementers’ conference. These included Malawi, Luxembourg, Pakistan, Zambia, Kenya, Tanzania, Nigeria, USA, Sri Lanka, China, Mozambique, Haiti, Rwanda, India, Algeria, Cameroon, China, Colombia, France, Germany, India, Namibia, Philippines, South Africa, and Uganda. The Minister of Health, represented by Dr. Sarah Byakika Assistant Commissioner Planning, presided over the conference opening. In her speech, she noted that the OpenMRS and the discussions of the conference contributed to outstanding improvement in health service delivery through improved electronic health information systems. She thanked the OpenMRS community picking Uganda as a host nation and that the Ministry’s pride in hosting the conference.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8442\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-8442 size-medium\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7267-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"METS Program Manager Evelyn Akello (L) and Prof. David Serwadda (R) during the Conference opening ceremony \" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> METS Program Manager Evelyn Akello (L) and Prof. David Serwadda (R) during the Conference opening ceremony[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe conference’s main highlights included the regular sessions, the unconference sessions where different topics were discussed concurrently in different halls; <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/0Bx19372m_9u6aWxNdGk0M3BybG8?usp=sharing\">lightening talks</a> that required the presenter to give a clear picture of how they were using OpenMRS and their milestones; demonstrations where presenters showcased how their national systems were operating; breakout sessions where delegates chose to attend the discussions of their interests in the various halls.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8441\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"290\"]<img class=\"wp-image-8441\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7296-300x178.jpg\" alt=\"IMG_7296\" width=\"290\" height=\"172\" /> Dr. Sarah Byakika (L) handing gifts to Dr. Biondich (C) and Dr. Burke (R) Mamlin as appreciation tokens for their contributions towards OpenMRS[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe participants were also given an opportunity to visit a variety of sites within Kampala that were using the system, these included; Kiruddu Hospital, Komamboga HC III, Kawala HC III, Kisugu HC III, Alive Medical Services (AMS), Kisenyi HC III and Family Hope Centre Ntinda.\r\n\r\nOpenMRS is a software platform and a reference application, that was created in 2004, which enables users to design customized medical records system with no programming knowledge. OpenMRS is based on the principle that information should be stored as summaries that make it easy to analyse by users at all levels. The OpenMRS community is a collective effort by a network of volunteers from many different backgrounds including technology, health care, and international development.\r\n\r\nThe Uganda National eHealth Policy has electronic medical records (EMR) management as a cornerstone for improving the quality of care provided to all Ugandans. The Ministry of Health (MoH), working closely with World Health Organization (WHO), Makerere University, School of Public Health’s Monitoring and Evaluation Technical Support (METS) with support from Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Uganda (CDC) piloted and adopted OpenMRS in 2011 as a national EMR to manage patient records. This system was customized to Uganda and is known as the UgandaEMR. The latest version (1.11.6) caters for more robust technological features on identifying and monitoring patients like use of a fingerprint feature. METS in partnership with various Implementing Partners has carried out massive country scale-up exercises with guidance from Ministry of Health and 400 facilities countrywide are using the system.\r\n\r\nThe Assistant Commissioner Division of Health Information and Chair of the Organising committee Dr. Eddie S. Mukooyo represented the Director General Health Sciences at the closing ceremony that was held on Friday, 9<sup>th</sup> December 2016. In his closing remarks, Dr. Mukooyo gave a heartfelt appreciation to the conference sponsors, PEPFAR Uganda which includes CDC and USAID, World Health Organization (WHO), Intelligent Medical Objects (IMO), Thought Works, Google and SolDevelo; for the support, they accorded the conference.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8444\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-8444 size-medium\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7436-1-300x158.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"158\" /> L-R: Dr. Eddie Mukooyo, Mr. Moses Bagyendera and Dr. Andrew Kanter during the lightening talks[/caption]\r\n\r\n<div class=\"mceTemp\">The conference was crowned with a two-day Hackathon that brought together the developers to find ways to best improve their national systems and discuss ways of making their systems work with similar features.</div>','2016 OPENMRS IMPLEMENTERS’ CONFERENCE','','publish','open','open','','2016-openmrs-implementers-conference','','','2017-01-20 12:58:02','2017-01-20 12:58:02','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?p=8436',0,'post','',0),(8441,2,'2017-01-20 12:24:21','2017-01-20 12:24:21','','IMG_7296','','inherit','open','closed','','img_7296','','','2017-01-20 12:24:21','2017-01-20 12:24:21','',8436,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7296.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8444,2,'2017-01-20 12:48:20','2017-01-20 12:48:20','','IMG_7436','L-R: Dr. Eddie Mukooyo, Dr.   and Dr. Andrew Kanter during the lightening talks','inherit','open','closed','','img_7436-2','','','2017-01-20 12:50:16','2017-01-20 12:50:16','',8436,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7436-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8447,2,'2017-01-24 09:28:12','2017-01-24 09:28:12','Makerere University School of Public Health’s Monitoring and Evaluation Technical Support (METS) Program designed a short-term M&amp;E fellowship program to reinforce the District and health facility capabilities in monitoring and evaluation. The Fellowship that targeted district biostatisticians and HMIS focal persons was held at Hotel Africana on 25th November 2016. The 30 Fellows from 15 districts in the 1st cohort was awarded completion certificates. The dissemination meeting was attended by representatives from the Ministry of Health, CDC, IPs, districts, MakSPH and METS.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8449\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-8449 size-medium\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7203-1-300x125.jpg\" alt=\"Fellows pose with the the Chief Guest representative from CDC Uganda, Dr. Donna Kabatesi, Evelyn Akello the Program Manager METS and Program facilitators \" width=\"300\" height=\"125\" /> Fellows pose with the the Chief Guest representative from CDC Uganda, Dr. Donna Kabatesi, Evelyn Akello the Program Manager METS and Program facilitators[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe two-modular fellowship program was aimed at achieving the following:\r\n1. Enhance M&amp;E capacity of District Health Teams and health facilities to effectively plan, manage and report quality data for HIV programs\r\n2. Supported the districts to develop HIV M&amp;E plans based on the 5-year HIV/AIDS strategic plans\r\n3. Strengthen QI along the Continuum of Response (COR) for HIV/AIDS\r\n4. Re-established QI teams in all health facilities which provide ART and PMTCT services\r\n5. Train 1,200 health facility staff in Quality Improvement principles\r\n6. Onsite Quality Improvement mentorship visits to 30 VMMC sites\r\n7. Supporting evidence-based policy development and advocacy for HIV programs\r\n8. Come up with strategies for improved retention in care HIV-infected mothers on Option B+\r\n9. Evaluation of strategies for improved pediatric outcomes among HIV exposed infants\r\n10. Evaluation of models for linking HIV patients into chronic HIV care and treatment\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8450\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-8450 size-medium\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7214-300x198.jpg\" alt=\"Some of the facilitators of the M&amp;E Fellowship Program L-R: Ms. Josephine Connie Ninsiima, Mr. Ibrahim Lutalo, Mr. Isaac Sebuliba, Mr. Julius Sendiwala and Project Coordinator Dr. Simon Muhumuza\" width=\"300\" height=\"198\" /> Some of the facilitators of the M&amp;E Fellowship Program<br /> L-R: Ms. Josephine Connie Ninsiima, Mr. Ibrahim Lutalo, Mr. Isaac Sebuliba, Mr. Julius Sendiwala and Project Coordinator Dr. Simon Muhumuza[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe meeting provided an opportunity for the fellows to disseminate their project results to a wider HIV/AIDS stakeholder forum. This involved sharing the project outcomes, best practices, lessons learnt and challenges in improving data quality for HIV/AIDS programs at district and health facility level. It is hoped that similar projects may be adopted and scaled nationally.','Final Dissemination Meeting for short-term M&E Fellows 2016','','publish','open','open','','final-dissemination-meeting-for-short-term-me-fellows-2016','','','2017-01-24 09:38:16','2017-01-24 09:38:16','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?p=8447',0,'post','',0),(8448,2,'2017-01-24 08:36:19','2017-01-24 08:36:19','','IMG_7203','','inherit','open','closed','','img_7203','','','2017-01-24 08:36:19','2017-01-24 08:36:19','',8447,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7203.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8449,2,'2017-01-24 08:37:34','2017-01-24 08:37:34','','IMG_7203','Fellows pose with the  the Chief Guest representative from CDC Uganda, Dr. Donna Kabatesi, Evelyn Akello the Program Manager METS and Program facilitators  ','inherit','open','closed','','img_7203-2','','','2017-01-24 08:41:08','2017-01-24 08:41:08','',8447,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7203-1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8450,2,'2017-01-24 08:45:56','2017-01-24 08:45:56','','IMG_7214','Some of the facilitators of the M&E Fellowship Program \nL-R: Ms. Josephine Connie Ninsiima, Mr. Ibrahim Lutalo, Mr. Isaac Sebuliba, Mr. Julius Sendiwala and Project Coordinator Dr. Simon Muhumuza','inherit','open','closed','','img_7214','','','2017-01-24 08:48:02','2017-01-24 08:48:02','',8447,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7214.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8452,2,'2017-01-24 09:32:02','2017-01-24 09:32:02','','IMG_6964','Ms. Evelyn Akello pledged continued support from METS to the Fellows who received Certificates of Attendance','inherit','open','closed','','img_6964','','','2017-01-24 09:37:52','2017-01-24 09:37:52','',8447,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_6964.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8457,1,'2017-01-24 14:31:31','2017-01-24 14:31:31','','slider-img','','inherit','open','closed','','slider-img','','','2017-01-24 14:31:31','2017-01-24 14:31:31','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/slider-img.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8461,2,'2017-01-25 14:28:37','2017-01-25 14:28:37','Thirty representatives of the sixteen CDC supported Implementing Partners (IPs) converged at the Monitoring and Evaluation Technical Support (METS) Program office on 20<sup>th</sup> January 2016 in a bid to demystify the MER 2.0 tool kit. MER 2.0 is a set of PEPFAR indicators that focus on HIV Prevention &amp; Support, Knowing HIV Status, On ART and Viral Suppression. The orientation was conduct by members of the MIS team from METS; Mr. Eric Munyambabazi, Mrs. Jennifer Balaba-Bogere and Mr. Herbert Mulira.\r\n\r\nDr. Jennifer Galibraith, from CDC Uganda noted the need for the IPs to work together for the sake of achieving more. She applauded the different teams for the work done this far and that she was looking forward to the work ahead.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8462\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-8462 size-medium\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7596-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"CDC\'s Jennifer Galbraith making her remarks\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" /> CDC\'s Jennifer Galbraith making her remarks[/caption]\r\n\r\nThose in attendance included representatives from AMREF, Children AIDS Fund, Infectious Disease Institute (IDI), Baylor Uganda, Mildmay Uganda, Reach Out Mbuya, TASO Uganda, Makerere University Joint AIDS Program (MJAP), Rakai Health Sciences Project (RHSP), Uganda Prisons, Uganda Catholic Medical Bureau, Uganda Protestant Medical Bureau and Medical Access.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8464\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-8464 size-medium\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7612-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"Some of the IP representatives that attended the Orientation \" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> Some of the IP representatives that attended the Orientation[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Overview of PEPFAR MER 2.0</strong>\r\n\r\nThe President\'s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR) focus on impact in individuals and communities is the driving force for an effective framework that not only monitors outputs from the program but also key outcomes. PEPFAR is partnering with the international community – such as Uganda to drive towards the UNAIDS 90-90-90 global goals: 90 percent of people living with HIV know their HIV status, 90 percent of people who know their HIV status are accessing treatment, and 90 percent of people on treatment have suppressed viral loads.\r\n\r\nIn addition to the treatment indicators, the program will continue to measure our prevention goals, including through Voluntary Medical Male Circumcision and in 2017 moving the key DREAMS (Determined, Resilient, Empowered, AIDS-free, Mentored, and Safe) indicators into the Monitoring, Evaluation and Results (MER). The MER indicators additionally monitor HIV/TB indicators that will continue to drive the implementation of TB Preventive (IPT) policy.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_8463\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-8463 size-medium\" src=\"http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7607-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"&quot;Reporting quarter regulations differ for different mechanisms, hence it is important to use the required regulations as provided by National, CDC or PEPFAR&quot; Mrs. Jennifer Balaba-Bogere\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /> \"Reporting quarter regulations differ for different mechanisms, hence it is important to use the required regulations as provided by National, CDC or PEPFAR\" Mrs. Jennifer Balaba-Bogere[/caption]\r\n\r\nGiven the global HIV progress over the past decade, planning, monitoring and resource allocation needs to occur at district and community levels in order to have the most impact. Collection and use of data that represents populations served and geographic areas down to the site level where the services are being offered are critical in understanding current program performance and planning for future performance. The indicators continue to evolve to reflect the evolution of the USG support to measure both the impact of National and Regional support through host governm\r\n\r\nnts down to direct services at the site.\r\n\r\n<strong>The PEPFAR MER 2.0 Indicators focuses on the following:</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Reduction of indicators to focus program monitoring on what matters most for epidemic control</li>\r\n 	<li>Standardization of age, sex and key population disaggregation across prevention and clinical cascades to monitor which populations are being reached with high quality evidence-based services, and to identify which populations are not being reached</li>\r\n 	<li>Continuous alignment of indicators with multilaterals and partner governments to avoid duplication of data collection where possible and to focus on improved data quality and programmatic quality</li>\r\n 	<li>Aligned frequency of reporting across indicators to ensure that results are actionable within the period that they are reported</li>\r\n 	<li>Input from community stakeholders, technical experts, implementing partners, and field staff</li>\r\n 	<li>Alignment with other PEPFAR data streams such as site improvement of monitoring systems, expenditure analysis and the sustainability index</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;','CDC IPs GET ORIENTED ON THE MER 2.0','','publish','open','open','','cdc-ips-get-oriented-on-the-mer-2-0','','','2017-01-25 14:28:37','2017-01-25 14:28:37','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?p=8461',0,'post','',0),(8462,2,'2017-01-25 14:07:45','2017-01-25 14:07:45','','IMG_7596','CDC\'s Jennifer Galbraith making her remarks','inherit','open','closed','','img_7596','','','2017-01-25 14:08:24','2017-01-25 14:08:24','',8461,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7596.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8463,2,'2017-01-25 14:11:31','2017-01-25 14:11:31','','IMG_7607','\"Reporting quarter regulations differ for different mechanisms, hence it is important to use the required regulations as provided by National, CDC or PEPFAR\" Mrs. Jennifer Balaba-Bogere','inherit','open','closed','','img_7607','','','2017-01-25 14:15:10','2017-01-25 14:15:10','',8461,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7607.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8464,2,'2017-01-25 14:19:27','2017-01-25 14:19:27','','IMG_7612','Some of the IP representatives that attended the Orientation ','inherit','open','closed','','img_7612','','','2017-01-25 14:21:45','2017-01-25 14:21:45','',8461,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7612.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8466,2,'2017-01-25 14:31:00','2017-01-25 14:31:00','','IMG_7614','METS facilitated a PEPFAR Monitoring,  Evaluation and Results (MER) 2.0 Tool Kit Orientation ','inherit','open','closed','','img_7614','','','2017-01-25 14:32:47','2017-01-25 14:32:47','',8461,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/IMG_7614.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8469,2,'2017-01-27 13:27:21','2017-01-27 13:27:21','In line with our mandate to support CQI for SMC services, the M&amp;E Project will conduct a joint on-site mentorship and quality assessments for all the 57 CDC supported VMMC sites in Uganda. This activity is intended to;\r\n\r\ni) assess the quality of SMC services offered at each site using the MOH SMC Quality assessment tool,\r\n\r\nii) identify SMC service quality gaps and develop action plans for continuous quality improvement,\r\n\r\niii) collect data on TT vaccination,\r\n\r\niv) SMC data validation for the period October-December 2016.\r\n\r\nThe visits will be jointly conducted with the supporting IPs and MoH.','SMC Quality Improvement Assessment and Mentorship','','publish','closed','closed','','smc-quality-improvement-assessment-and-mentorship','','','2017-01-27 13:27:21','2017-01-27 13:27:21','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8469',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8470,2,'2017-01-27 13:51:45','2017-01-27 13:51:45','METS is planning to cnduct an HMIS tools status assessment at selected health facilities to ascertain the tools usage and status at the health facilities','HMIS Tools Status Assessment','','publish','closed','closed','','hmis-tools-status-assessment','','','2017-01-27 13:54:51','2017-01-27 13:54:51','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8470',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8471,2,'2017-01-27 14:12:36','2017-01-27 14:12:36','Developers from METS will be collaborating with Kenyan counterparts to brainstorm best practices and how to integrate DHIS2 into UgandaEMR.\r\n\r\nThis meeting will take place in Nairobi-Kenya, also attending the meeting will be representatives from the MoH, CDC and METS management','Uganda-Kenya Electronic Medical Records Meeting','','publish','closed','closed','','uganda-kenya-electronic-medical-records-meeting','','','2017-01-27 14:12:36','2017-01-27 14:12:36','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?post_type=ajde_events&#038;p=8471',0,'ajde_events','',0),(8473,1,'2017-01-30 06:08:08','2017-01-30 06:08:08','[vc_row][vc_column][vc_custom_heading text=\"Read online or Download our <strong>Quarterly</strong> Newsletter\" google_fonts=\"font_family:Lato%3A100%2C100italic%2C300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C700%2C700italic%2C900%2C900italic|font_style:300%20light%20regular%3A300%3Anormal\"][vc_accordion][vc_accordion_tab title=\"2016 First, Second and Third quoter\"][vc_column_text]Greetings from METS\r\n\r\nThe Program has rolled out well and this year it comes with the promise of great growth and change. As part of our own expansion and growth, we are excited to launch our first issue and we hope that you find it enlightening, we will continue to update you on our ongoing projects as the year rolls out. Please share or tell a friend to tell a friend.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0BzMWf_9ra12sdlh3Z3NjOWZ3NTFHX0g2Qy12SlNMV00zSGRR\">READ or DOWNLOAD PDF FILE HERE</a>\r\n\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title=\"2016 OpenMRS Newsletter \"][vc_column_text]The 2016 OpenMRS International Implementers\' Conference was held in Uganda in December 2016. This <a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B4jwP0ShI6fCM19Hb1paMlUxbGs\">Newsletter </a>highlights the events and activities of the six day conference at the Speke Resort Munyonyo[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][/vc_accordion][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Newsletters','','publish','closed','closed','','newsletters','','','2017-03-27 09:08:26','2017-03-27 09:08:26','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?page_id=8473',0,'page','',0),(8475,1,'2017-01-30 06:09:38','2017-01-30 06:09:38',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','newsletters','','','2017-07-06 04:57:45','2017-07-06 04:57:45','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?p=8475',13,'nav_menu_item','',0),(8482,1,'2017-02-01 15:16:23','2017-02-01 15:16:23','[vc_row css=\".vc_custom_1474965242775{margin-bottom: 0px !important;}\" parallax_background=\"\"][vc_column][vc_column_text]\r\n<h3>Through the Health Management Information Systems, Program Area D (HMIS), METS is Aiming at:-</h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li><strong>I</strong>mproving patient <span style=\"color: #008000;\">identification</span>, tracking, service provision and referrals of persons with HIVs along the clinical cascade.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>I</strong>ncrease availability of <span style=\"color: #993300;\">critical <strong>HMIS</strong> tools</span> at health facilities to facilitate <span style=\"color: #008000;\"><strong>data</strong> collection and reporting</span>.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>E</strong>stablish and expand functional electronic HMIS at national, districts and high volume facilities</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>I</strong>mprove <em><strong><span style=\"color: #008000;\">data quality</span></strong></em> and use for <span style=\"color: #993300;\">better planning</span> and decision-making at district and facility levels.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>S</strong>trengthen ordering and reporting of <span style=\"color: #008000;\">ARVs</span> and <span style=\"color: #008000;\">HIV</span> test kits using the web-based ordering system (WAOS).</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>E</strong>stablish a data-sharing platform which pulls data from <em>DATIM</em>, <em>DHIS2</em> and other sources to act as a central repository for <span style=\"color: #008000;\">HIV data</span>.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n[/vc_column_text][vc_single_image image=\"8483\" img_size=\"600x300\" alignment=\"center\" style=\"vc_box_border\" hover_effect=\"img_reduce_opacity\"][vc_custom_heading text=\"The <strong>projects interventions</strong>\" font_container=\"tag:h2|font_size:30|text_align:left\" google_fonts=\"font_family:Lato%3A100%2C100italic%2C300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C700%2C700italic%2C900%2C900italic|font_style:300%20light%20regular%3A300%3Anormal\" el_class=\"letterspacing-2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 5\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n\r\nIn 2015, The Ministry of Health approved OpenMRS as an electronic patient records system and indicated the need to expand the system to cater for all the other program areas. With support from CDC, METS in 2015 received support to customize and support the national scale-up of OpenMRS. METS upgraded the existing OpenMRS (Version 1.6.3 to Version 1.11.6 which was rebranded from OpenMRS to UgandaEMR. <a href=\"http://emrportal.mets.or.ug/\" target=\"_blank\">VISIT THE PORTAL</a>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n[/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=\"HMIS Tools\" font_container=\"tag:h2|font_size:30|text_align:left\" google_fonts=\"font_family:Lato%3A100%2C100italic%2C300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C700%2C700italic%2C900%2C900italic|font_style:300%20light%20regular%3A300%3Anormal\" el_class=\"letterspacing-2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 5\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n\r\n<em><strong>METS printed critical HMIS tools</strong></em> including Registers, Forms and Clients Cards for the entire country. All (100%) of the 44 critical HMIS tools were printed and majority distributed through Implementing Partners, districts and to the health facilities for further knowledge generation and sharing.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n[/vc_column_text][vc_single_image image=\"7735\" img_size=\"medium\" alignment=\"center\" style=\"vc_box_shadow_circle\" onclick=\"zoom\" hover_effect=\"img_reduce_opacity\"][vc_custom_heading text=\"Capacity Building\" font_container=\"tag:h2|font_size:30|text_align:left\" google_fonts=\"font_family:Lato%3A100%2C100italic%2C300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C700%2C700italic%2C900%2C900italic|font_style:300%20light%20regular%3A300%3Anormal\" el_class=\"letterspacing-2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 5\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n\r\nFor sustainability as far as capacity building is concerned, METS in collaboration with the Ministry of Health, Division of Health Information, <a href=\"http://www.who.int/\" target=\"_blank\">WHO</a> and <a href=\"https://www.cdc.gov/\" target=\"_blank\">CDC</a> organized the first ever National OpenMRS Trainer of Trainers in Mbarara to build capacity countrywide. The workshop provided participants with practical hands on training on the updated <a href=\"http://emrportal.mets.or.ug/\" target=\"_blank\">UgandaEMR</a> system. The training that targeted IT and M&amp;E staff from various CDC and USAID supported Implementing Partners (IPs). The 120 participants that relate with the use of OpenMRS across the country.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n[/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=\"Strategic <strong>Planning Workshops</strong>\" font_container=\"tag:h2|font_size:30|text_align:left\" google_fonts=\"font_family:Lato%3A100%2C100italic%2C300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C700%2C700italic%2C900%2C900italic|font_style:300%20light%20regular%3A300%3Anormal\" el_class=\"letterspacing-2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 5\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n\r\n<strong>DHIS2 Technical Support to Ministry of Health:</strong> METS supported the Ministry of Health to conduct two eHMIS orientation trainings for the National Level Programs and Armed forces (police, Army and Prisons). To maintain a reliable national eHMIS system, the project further supported the Ministry of Health to customize the national DHIS2. Missing data validation rules and indicators for the different program areas including TB, and Malaria, were identified and integrated into the national DHIS2 during the quarter.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n\r\n<strong>EOC-MOH support:</strong> METS supported the Emergency Operation Centre (EOC) with eMTCT Option B+ and Retention Reporting. The project supported the MoH to schedule weekly presentations and sent out reminders for reporting, and presentations to the different stakeholders. The <a href=\"http://dashboard.mets.or.ug\" target=\"_blank\">Option B+ report platform</a>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n\r\n<strong>HIV Situation Room:</strong> Together with the Ministry of Health, the Division of Health Information, participated in a study tour on the Situation Room in Nairobi. The Situation Room provides a platform for managers to have access to data from different data sources to make accurate decisions a concept that METS plans to support the Ministry of Health in. <a href=\"http://mets.or.ug\">METS</a> is now working out a concepts to have this implemented in Uganda.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"column\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n[/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=\"<strong>Innovations</strong>\" font_container=\"tag:h2|font_size:30|text_align:left\" google_fonts=\"font_family:Lato%3A100%2C100italic%2C300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C700%2C700italic%2C900%2C900italic|font_style:300%20light%20regular%3A300%3Anormal\" el_class=\"letterspacing-2\"][vc_column_text]\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 5\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n\r\n<strong>These @METS</strong> include Health Informatics Mapper known as the <em><strong>HiMap</strong></em>. This is an eHealth strategic information application that can be used to capture the GIS coordinates for the District Health Offices and Health Facilities across the country. The application will also enable the user to access the District Health Offices and Health Facilities across the country.\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 5\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n\r\n<strong>The Strategic Information Mobile Application and Option B+ Dashboard</strong>\r\n\r\nThis is a mobile based application that was developed by METS for the Ministry of Health to monitor the Elimination of Mother To Child Transmission (<em><strong>eMTCT</strong></em>) of HIV program.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\"></div>\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\"></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n[/vc_column_text][vc_custom_heading text=\"<strong>Publications</strong> | <i>Articles, Papers &amp; Bulletin</i>\" font_container=\"tag:h2|font_size:30|text_align:left\" google_fonts=\"font_family:Lato%3A100%2C100italic%2C300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C700%2C700italic%2C900%2C900italic|font_style:300%20light%20regular%3A300%3Anormal\" el_class=\"letterspacing-2\"][vc_column_text el_class=\"publication\"]\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B4jwP0ShI6fCSmtEdl90ckpPMmdNOTRJaVJtQkRPSjVNTC0w\"> CypherHealth Uganda: An automated health facility coding and inventory system for Uganda | </a><em>by Stephen Ocaya, Eric Munyambabazi, and Jonathan Mpango.</em></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B4jwP0ShI6fCaURQZzRfaC1Gb3dQMDFNN0dPeWxRZ3ZHdnZJ\">eHealth Bulletin Issue 2 - September 2016</a> |<em>Contributor - Mr. Jonathan Mpango &amp; Samuel Lubwama – Makerere University School of Public </em><em>Health, METS Program</em></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B4jwP0ShI6fCT2VEVWlPT042YjRkOXBrNXU5WUtxel8yaHNv\">ROLLOUT OF PATIENTS ELECTRONIC MANAGEMENT RECORDS SYSTEM IN UGANDA (UGANDAEMR)</a> | <em>Author: Mwotasubi Isaac, Ocaya Stephen, Charity Kyomugasho, Evelyn Akello, </em>William Bazeyo.</li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B4jwP0ShI6fCYVRveVBhNUR4aTlpS3pCSmxOeUxpZjhoMkFz\">The Use of Dashboards in Performance Management for Public Health Interventions in Uganda: A Case of Option B+ Surveillance</a> | <em>by Kaye Milton. Makerere University School of Public Health, METS Program.</em></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B4jwP0ShI6fCU2thc1ZROW1JdDRfNE5UbDVqbGhMbXJQbWZB\">Empowering girls and reducing HIV infections by the DREAMS Program</a> | <em>by Daisy Shirley Kusiima</em></li>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B4jwP0ShI6fCdC1CWHlITno4aElzNWhoOEcwSm5BY2lXdjE0\">e-Health Bulletin Issue 1 - April 2016</a> | <em>by By Mr. Moses Bagyendera, WHO-Uganda | Writers  Jonathan Mpango</em></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p class=\"page\" title=\"Page 5\"><em> </em></p>\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Health Management Information Systems','','publish','closed','closed','','health-management-information-systems','','','2017-03-23 14:42:49','2017-03-23 14:42:49','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?page_id=8482',0,'page','',0),(8483,1,'2017-02-01 13:48:14','2017-02-01 13:48:14','','health-management-information-system-1-638','','inherit','open','closed','','health-management-information-system-1-638','','','2017-02-01 13:48:14','2017-02-01 13:48:14','',8482,'http://mets.or.ug/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/health-management-information-system-1-638.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(8485,1,'2017-02-01 15:22:07','2017-02-01 15:22:07',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','8485','','','2017-07-06 04:57:45','2017-07-06 04:57:45','',0,'http://mets.or.ug/?p=8485',10,'nav_menu_item','',0),(8494,1,'2017-02-03 09:00:50','2017-02-03 09:00:50','[vc_row][vc_column][vc_custom_heading text=\"CDC Funded Districts where <strong>METS Operate</strong> \" google_fonts=\"font_family:Lato%3A100%2C100italic%2C300%2C300italic%2Cregular%2Citalic%2C700%2C700italic%2C900%2C900italic|font_style:300%20l